        "id": "75b7ac27-4c00-4d91-a0ed-9209729e0524",
        "text": "The word is derived from the Doric ([[Dorians]]) word ''apella'' , which originally meant wall, enclosure of stones,  and later assembly  of people  within the limits of the square. It is derived from  the Ancient Greek ([[Ancient Greek language]]) word ''pélla'' , \"stone\", which appears in some toponyms in Greece like [[Pella]]  and Pallini . The explanation is given by  Hesychius ([[Hesychius of Alexandria]]): ''apellai'' , ''sekoi'' ( \"folds\"), ''ecclesiai'' (: popular assemblies). The festival ''[[apellai]]'' was surely dedicated to the god  [[Apollo]]  (Doric ([[Dorians]]) form: ) and it was  spread by the [[Dorians]] in central-Greece, as it is proved by the use of the month ''Apellaios'' ."
