        "id": "b044b0fd-cdc2-4ee3-a7f5-0e0aa75aaee1",
        "text": "The meetings had in all probability taken place originally in the Agora, but were later transferred to the neighbouring building known as the Skias. According to [[Plutarch]], a  [[Great Rhetra]]  was given by [[Pythia]] to Lycurgus ([[Lycurgus of Sparta]]). The old aristocratic council,  was  substituted by the [[gerousia]]  (thirty elders  including  the two kings). The meetings  of the   \"apella\" should take place from time to time, and the citizens should  have the power to debate and take the decisions.  This  right  of the citizens  was very soon  limited.  The kings Theopompus and Polydorus, probably during the 7th century BC, added to the \"rhetra\" that  the kings and the elders ([[gerousia]])  could set aside any \"crooked\" decision of the people."
